1338","1315–1377":"1315–1377","1240–1312":"1240–1312","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","from 20 February 1312 to 1320":"from 20 February 1312 to 1320","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","AFT 1338":"after 1338","1240":"1240","ABT 1290":"about 1290","1290":"1290","Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ramsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant (the usual spelling in Scotland) of   Ramsey  . The Scottish Ramsays derive from Simund <i>de Ramesie</i>, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsey","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Ramsay was born about 1290, in Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Edmond de Ramsay of Dalhousie. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1338."},"et":{"ABT 1290–AFT 1338":"umbes 1290–pärast 1338","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1315–1377":"1315–1377","1240–1312":"1240–1312","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","from 20 February 1312 to 1320":"20. veebruar 1312 kuni 1320","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","AFT 1338":"pärast 1338","1240":"1240","ABT 1290":"umbes 1290","1290":"1290","Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalhousie, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1290–AFT 1338":"noin 1290–1338 jälkeen","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1315–1377":"1315–1377","1240–1312":"1240–1312","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1377":"1377","from 20 February 1312 to 1320":"vuodesta 20. helmikuuta 1312 vuoteen 1320","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","AFT 1338":"1338 jälkeen","1240":"1240","ABT 1290":"noin 1290","1290":"1290","Dalhousie, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalhousie, Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1290–AFT 1338":"environ 1290–après 1338","1288–1342":"1288–1342","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1315–13